h two tithables in Henrico in 1679\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Land Deed\",\"d\":\"1680\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Abraham Childres [II or Jr] to John Pleasants, 140 acres on the north side of the James River that was purchased by his father Abram [Abraham] Childres of/from Major William Harris and was given to Abraham in Abram's will, 1680.\"},{\"t\":\"RESIDENCE\",\"ti\":\"\",\"d\":\"1 December 1681\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Jury Duty\",\"d\":\"1683\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Serves on the jury regarding a case of horse theft.\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Indian Slave Owner\",\"d\":\"1683\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"He owned an eight-year old Indian boy name James.\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Land Deed\",\"d\":\"1691\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"He deeded to John Pleasants, 12 acres on Four Mile Creek. Land he bought from Edward Mathews.\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Will Executed\",\"d\":\"1 June 1698\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Land Owner\",\"d\":\"1704\",\"pl\":\"Henrico, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"In 1704 Abraham Childers owned 368 acres in Henrico, \"}],\"mem\":2,\"src\":26,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LR62-18X\":{\"ev\":[],\"mem\":0,\"src\":0,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LR6L-Q4N\":{\"ev\":[],\"mem\":0,\"src\":0,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LR7T-FWX\":{\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Education\",\"d\":\"1624\",\"pl\":\"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom\",\"desc\":\"Graduated Oxford & Cambridge\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Education\",\"d\":\"1627\",\"pl\":\"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England\",\"desc\":\"College Graduation Pembroke College, Cambridge\"},{\"t\":\"IMMIGRATION\",\"ti\":\"\",\"d\":\"5 February 1631\",\"pl\":\"Boston, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"He arrived, with Mary, on 5 February 1631 at Boston in the Massachusetts Bay Colony. Their passage was aboard the ship Lyon (Lion). \"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"5 February 1631\",\"pl\":\"Boston, Suffolk, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"April 1631\",\"pl\":\"Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"August 1631\",\"pl\":\"Plymouth, Plymouth, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"1633\",\"pl\":\"Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Court\",\"d\":\"9 October 1635\",\"pl\":\"Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"The General Court sentenced him to banishment because he had \\\"broached and divulged new and dangerous opinions against the authority of magistrates, also written letters of defamation\\\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Fact\",\"d\":\"January 1636\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"The four men that aided Roger Williams in his escape from Salem, Ma in January 1636 were Thomas Angell (minor), William Harris, John Smith & Francis Wickes (minor)\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"January 1636\",\"pl\":\"Sowams, Bristol, Rhode Island, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Fact\",\"d\":\"1636\",\"pl\":\"Providence, Rhode Island, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Founding of Providence Plantations - Providence Plantations was the first permanent European American settlement in Rhode Island. It was established by a group of colonists led by Roger Williams and Dr. John Clarke . Providence Plantations became the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations, which became the State of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations after the American Revolution. The plantations were established along the Providence River with the main settlement at Providence in 1636 by Roger Williams, Dr. John Clarke and a small band of followers who had left the Massachusetts Bay Colony to seek freedom of worship. The settlers adopted a covenant which stressed the separation of religious and civil affairs.[2] Williams purchased Pawtuxet on the north side of the Pawtuxet River from the Narragansett sachems in 1638. Massachusetts Bay attempted to extend its authority over Providence Plantations and the settlements in Newport, Portsmouth, and Shawomet during the 1630s and 1640s. (Portsmouth and Newport were on Aquidneck Island, which was called Rhode Island at the time.) Williams traveled to London in 1643 to settle the matter, and in 1644 he received a parliamentary Commission for Plantations patent, uniting Providence with Portsmouth and Newport as \\\"The Incorporation of Providence Plantations in the Narraganset Bay in New England\\\".\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"1636\",\"pl\":\"Rock, Middleborough, Plymouth, Massachusetts, United States\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Move\",\"d\":\"about 1636\",\"pl\":\"Rhode Island, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"RELIGIOUS_AFFILIATION\",\"ti\":\"\",\"d\":\"1638\",\"pl\":\"Providence, Rhode Island, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Baptist - Founded the First Baptist Church in America\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Fact\",\"d\":\"1643\",\"pl\":\"London, England\",\"desc\":\"Publication of First Book- A Key into the Language of America\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Fact\",\"d\":\"1644\",\"pl\":\"London, England\",\"desc\":\"Publication of Williams most famous work - The Bloudy Tenent of Persecution for Cause of Conscience\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Fact\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"Roger Williams spoke at least seven different languages: English, French, Latin, Dutch, Greek, Hebrew, and Narragansett.\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Burials\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"Roger has been laid to rest three times! Roger was first buried behind his house on Towne Street at what is now North Main Street.     In 1860, his remains were moved to a family crypt in the Old North Burial Ground. A committee was formed to create a memorial to Williams and they selected Prospect Terrance as a suitable final resting place. However, funds were meager, the Civil War intervened and no action was taken.     To mark the 300th anniversary of the founding of Providence in 1936, a new committee raised funds and interred the remains under a statue of Williams, dedicated in 1939, at Prospect Terrace.\"}],\"mem\":68,\"src\":60,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LR88-B1K\":{\"ev\":[],\"mem\":0,\"src\":13,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LR8M-5K3\":{\"ev\":[],\"mem\":0,\"src\":0,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LR9P-H8K\":{\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Captain of \\\"The Graft\\\" owned by Governor Wouter\",\"d\":\"1653\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Capt. of \\\"Flower of Gelder\\\"\",\"d\":\"1655\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"He & Annekin lived Poor Bowery\",\"d\":\"1655\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Capt. of \\\"De St.Jan Baptist\\\"\",\"d\":\"1657\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"bought land in Brooklyn near ferry\",\"d\":\"1662\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"on tax list of Brooklyn worth 120#\",\"d\":\"1676\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"}],\"mem\":3,\"src\":7,\"sketch\":\"\"},\"LRB5-HFB\":{\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"AFN\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"9MFD-KJ\"},{\"t\":\"OCCUPATION\",\"ti\":\"\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"Vineyard Haven, Tisbury, Dukes, Massachusetts, United States\",\"desc\":\"Blacksmith\"},{\"t\":\"RELIGIOUS_AFFILIATION\",\"ti\":\"\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc